export const module1Slides = [
  {title: "Welcome Letter from the CEO", content: "Dear Team Member,\n\nWelcome to Milk Pop.\n\nI am proud to welcome you to the beginning of your journey with our brand.\n\nMilk Pop was created with a simple idea: to make everyday treat moments feel bright, easy and memorable. To a customer, this may look like a milkshake, a smoothie, a soft serve or a slush. But behind every product, there is a standard. There is a way of speaking, a way of preparing, a way of serving and a way of caring.\n\nYou are not joining Milk Pop only to prepare drinks. You are joining a brand where your actions matter. The way you greet a customer, the way you communicate with your team, the way you keep your space clean, the way you stay calm during a queue and the way you present a finished product all become part of the Milk Pop experience.\n\nI want every team member to feel that this role can give something back to them. Some people will become more confident. Some will improve their communication. Some will learn how to stay calm under pressure. Some will grow into leadership. Everyone should be able to take something valuable from their time here.\n\nMilk Pop is built on communication, respect and dedication to what we do.\n\nWe are excited to support our staff in every possible way. That means clear training, better systems, useful software, improved operations, strong equipment, practical tools and a working environment that helps people succeed. We will keep improving the business so the team can perform with confidence.\n\nIn return, we expect effort, honesty, reliability and a serious attitude towards success. Support works best when both sides are committed. We will provide the tools and the opportunity. You must bring the care, discipline and willingness to grow.\n\nOur customer promise is simple:\n\nSip • Smile • Enjoy\n\nBehind that promise is a team that is trained, supported and proud of the standard it delivers.\n\nWelcome to Milk Pop.\n\nLukas Cekanauskas\nFounder & CEO\nMilk Pop"},
  {title: "More Than a Job", content: "Before learning the menu, the prices or the procedures, it is important to understand what this role can become.\n\nMilk Pop may be a simple treat brand for customers, but working here can build serious professional skills. Every shift gives you a chance to practise communication, patience, confidence, awareness, teamwork and responsibility.\n\nYou may learn how to speak to customers with more confidence. You may learn how to stay calm when the environment becomes busy. You may learn how to notice problems earlier, organise your work better, support teammates more naturally or take feedback with maturity.\n\nThis is why Milk Pop does not see training as a formality. Training is part of how we help people grow.\n\nThe role is not only about what you make. It is also about who you become while doing the work."},
  {title: "What Milk Pop Is", content: "Milk Pop is a shopping centre treat brand built around milkshakes, smoothies, soft serve, slush and simple extras.\n\nOur menu is focused because the customer experience should be easy. People walking through a shopping centre often make quick decisions. They may be with friends, with children, carrying bags, taking a break or simply passing by. They should be able to understand Milk Pop quickly and feel confident ordering without confusion.\n\nMilkshakes are the heart of the brand. They are the product customers should immediately associate with us. Smoothies, soft serve, slush and extras complete the experience by giving customers more ways to enjoy a quick treat.\n\nA simple menu does not mean simple standards. It means every product must be prepared with care, consistency and pride."},
  {title: "Simple for the Customer", content: "The best customer experiences often feel effortless.\n\nA customer walks up, understands the menu, receives a friendly greeting, chooses a flavour, adds an extra if they wish, pays, waits briefly and receives a product that looks correct and enjoyable.\n\nFrom the outside, it feels simple.\n\nBehind the counter, that simple experience depends on many standards working together. The order must be taken accurately. The correct size must be prepared. The station must stay clean. The product must be presented properly. The customer must feel acknowledged. If something goes wrong, it must be corrected calmly.\n\nThis is one of the most important principles at Milk Pop:\n\nThe experience should feel simple because the team is professional."},
  {title: "Our Culture", content: "Milk Pop is built on three foundations: communication, respect and dedication.\n\nCommunication means we speak clearly, listen properly and raise issues early. We do not wait for small problems to become serious. We ask when unsure, we share important information and we keep the team aware during busy periods.\n\nRespect means we treat customers, teammates and the workplace with care. We speak professionally. We do not embarrass others. We do not blame people in front of customers. We understand that every role matters.\n\nDedication means we care about the details even when the task looks simple. A clean counter matters. A correct order matters. A polite handover matters. A well-restocked station matters. Small details create the standard.\n\nThis culture is not created by posters or slogans. It is created by how the team behaves every day."},
  {title: "Staff Are the Brand", content: "A brand is not only a logo, colour palette or menu board.\n\nA brand becomes real when a customer interacts with the people behind it.\n\nAt Milk Pop, customers experience the brand through your greeting, your tone, your speed, your cleanliness, your confidence and your reaction under pressure. They may not remember every detail of the menu, but they will remember whether the service felt warm, organised and worth returning for.\n\nThis means every team member carries responsibility.\n\nWhen you serve well, you build trust. When you stay calm during pressure, you protect the experience. When you clean as you go, you make the kiosk feel safe and professional. When you recommend clearly, you help customers choose. When you take ownership of a mistake, you show maturity.\n\nThe team is the brand in action."},
  {title: "Why Growth Matters", content: "Milk Pop is preparing to grow, but growth is not created only by marketing, design or social media. Those things may bring attention. They do not create loyalty by themselves.\n\nLoyalty is built through repeated good experiences.\n\nA customer tries Milk Pop once. The product looks right. The service feels friendly. The kiosk looks clean. The order is correct. The price feels fair. The customer leaves happy. Later, they return. They bring a friend. They recommend it. They choose Milk Pop again during another shopping trip.\n\nThis is how a brand grows.\n\nEvery shift contains moments that either build or weaken trust. A small action can matter more than it seems. A clear recommendation, a clean counter, a kind response or a well-handled mistake can be the reason a customer comes back.\n\nWhen the brand grows, opportunities grow with it. Growth can create more hours, more roles, more responsibility and more future leadership opportunities for the team.\n\nBusiness growth is not separate from daily service. It is created by it."},
  {title: "What We Give, What We Expect", content: "Milk Pop is committed to supporting staff properly.\n\nSupport means giving people the right tools to succeed. That includes training that explains the role clearly, systems that make work easier, software that helps organisation, equipment that supports better service, and operations that continue improving as the business grows.\n\nWe do not expect people to succeed without structure.\n\nAt the same time, support must work both ways.\n\nMilk Pop can provide the tools, the standards and the opportunity. The team member must bring effort, honesty, reliability and willingness to improve. A strong workplace is built when the business invests in people and people take pride in their role.\n\nThis is the balance we believe in:\n\nWe support your success.\nYou work towards the standard."},
  {title: "The Shopping Centre Environment", content: "Working in a shopping centre is different from working in a quiet café or restaurant.\n\nThe pace can change suddenly. One moment may be quiet, and the next moment there may be a queue. Customers may be in a hurry. Families may be managing children. Groups may order together and change their minds. People may ask questions while you are already preparing another order. The environment may be loud, distracting and busy.\n\nThis is normal.\n\nThe goal is not to avoid pressure. The goal is to stay professional inside it.\n\nPressure will test your focus, patience and communication. It may make you want to rush. It may make small mistakes more likely. It may make customers feel impatient. In those moments, your training matters.\n\nAt Milk Pop, calm service is stronger than rushed service. Speed matters, but accuracy still matters. Friendliness matters, but safety still matters. A queue should never make us careless."},
  {title: "The Psychology of Service", content: "Customers do not always say what they are thinking.\n\nA customer may be wondering whether the kiosk looks clean, whether the product is worth the price, whether their child will like the flavour, whether the staff know what they are doing, whether the queue will move quickly or whether they are welcome to ask a question.\n\nGood staff reduce uncertainty.\n\nConfidence from the team creates comfort for the customer. A clear greeting, a simple recommendation and a calm tone can make the customer feel safe choosing. This is especially important in a shopping centre, where people often decide quickly whether to stop or keep walking.\n\nCustomer service is not only about being polite. It is about understanding what the customer may need before they fully explain it."},
  {title: "The Mental Skills You Will Build", content: "Milk Pop develops mental skills that matter in any career.\n\nYou will practise focus by staying present with the order in front of you. You will build awareness by noticing the queue, the counter, the stock levels and the customer’s behaviour. You will strengthen memory by learning flavours, prices, sizes and procedures. You will develop emotional control by staying professional when customers are impatient or when the environment becomes busy.\n\nYou will also develop judgement. During a shift, not everything can be handled at once. You will learn how to choose the next right action, how to ask for support early and how to recover after a mistake.\n\nThe best team members are not the people who never feel pressure. They are the people who learn how to remain effective under pressure."},
  {title: "The Physical Reality", content: "Milk Pop service can be physically demanding.\n\nA shift may involve standing for long periods, moving quickly in a small space, cleaning regularly, restocking products, reaching, bending, lifting light supplies and repeating tasks during busy periods. This requires energy and awareness.\n\nWorking fast should never mean working unsafely.\n\nYour station should be organised so you can move efficiently. Spills should be handled quickly. Stock should be lifted safely. Hazards should be reported. If equipment feels unsafe, it should not be ignored. If you need help, you should ask.\n\nProfessional service includes looking after yourself and your team.\n\nA strong team does not wait for someone to struggle silently. A strong team communicates early, supports each other and protects the working environment."},
  {title: "Emotional Pressure", content: "Customer-facing work can be emotionally demanding.\n\nYou may face impatience, complaints, repeated questions, customers watching you closely, pressure from queues or frustration after making a mistake. This does not mean you are failing. It means you are working in a real service environment.\n\nEmotional control does not mean pretending nothing affects you. It means learning how to pause, breathe, respond clearly and choose the next professional action.\n\nIf a customer is frustrated, your calmness can reduce the pressure. If a mistake happens, your honesty can protect trust. If the queue grows, your structure can protect accuracy. If you feel overwhelmed, asking for support early is better than silently losing control.\n\nYou cannot control every customer reaction.\n\nYou can control your response."},
  {title: "Cleanliness and Trust", content: "Cleanliness is one of the strongest signals of professionalism.\n\nA customer may not know how a milkshake is prepared, but they can see whether the counter is sticky. They can see whether cups are handled properly. They can see whether the team looks clean and organised. They can see whether spills are ignored.\n\nIf the kiosk looks messy, customers may question the product.\n\nCleanliness is not only a closing task. It is part of service throughout the shift. Clean as you go. Keep your area ready. Do not wait for small mess to become a visible problem.\n\nA clean kiosk helps customers trust us. It helps the team move faster. It improves safety. It protects the brand.\n\nClean is not extra.\n\nClean is the standard."},
  {title: "Customer Awareness", content: "Different customers need different types of support.\n\nSome customers know exactly what they want. They need fast and accurate service. Some customers are unsure. They need a simple recommendation. Some customers are choosing for children. They may need help choosing something familiar. Some customers are in a rush. They need clarity. Some customers are curious. They may ask about flavours, sizes or extras.\n\nGood service is not saying the same thing to everyone in the same way.\n\nGood service is noticing what the customer needs and responding with confidence.\n\nA customer who likes chocolate may appreciate a recommendation such as Kinder Bueno, Oreo or Ferrero Rocher. A customer who wants something fruity may prefer Strawberry Banana, Mango Passion Fruit or Berry Mix. A customer who wants a larger treat may appreciate being told about the 400 ml option.\n\nWhen staff know the menu, they reduce customer uncertainty.\n\nMenu knowledge is customer care."},
  {title: "Mistakes and Recovery", content: "Mistakes can happen in any service environment.\n\nWhat matters is how they are handled.\n\nA professional team member does not hide a mistake, blame someone else or argue with the customer. A professional team member stays calm, acknowledges the issue and takes the next correct action.\n\nA simple phrase can protect the situation:\n\n“Sorry about that. I’ll fix it for you now.”\n\nThis kind of response shows maturity. It tells the customer that the team is in control. It prevents a small mistake from becoming a bigger problem.\n\nA mistake handled badly can damage trust.\n\nA mistake handled well can still protect the relationship."},
  {title: "Team Culture", content: "Milk Pop should be a place where team members feel supported, but also understand that standards matter.\n\nA strong team communicates early. If stock is running low, they say it before it becomes urgent. If the queue is growing, they support each other. If an area becomes messy, they clean it without waiting to be asked. If they are unsure, they ask instead of guessing.\n\nTeamwork does not mean everyone doing the same task.\n\nIt means everyone understanding what the shift needs.\n\nThe customer should not feel internal stress, poor communication or tension between staff. Behind the counter, the team must stay respectful, focused and professional.\n\nWe protect the customer experience together."},
  {title: "Dedication to the Standard", content: "Dedication is not about doing something dramatic. It is about caring consistently.\n\nIt means checking the order before preparing it. It means wiping the counter before it looks bad. It means speaking with patience when a customer is unsure. It means asking for help before a problem grows. It means taking feedback seriously instead of taking it personally.\n\nAt Milk Pop, we respect people who care about the small things.\n\nThe small things become the standard.\nThe standard becomes the experience.\nThe experience becomes the brand."},
  {title: "How to Succeed at Milk Pop", content: "Success at Milk Pop is built through consistent habits.\n\nLearn the menu properly. Arrive ready. Keep your station clean. Speak to customers with warmth and clarity. Work with urgency, but do not become careless. Take feedback professionally. Ask questions early. Care about details. Respect your teammates. Stay calm when the environment becomes busy.\n\nYou do not need to be perfect on your first day.\n\nYou do need to take the role seriously.\n\nMilk Pop will give you training, structure and support. In return, we expect effort, honesty, reliability and pride in the standard.\n\nProgress matters. Standards matter. Attitude matters."},
  {title: "Your Professional Commitment", content: "Before completing this module, take a moment to understand what you are committing to.\n\nYour actions affect customers. Your actions affect your team. Your actions affect the Milk Pop brand. A clean counter, a correct order, a calm response and a friendly handover all matter.\n\nThis academy is part of your staff record because training matters. The final assessment is formal because the role carries responsibility.\n\nBy continuing, you confirm that you understand the Milk Pop standard and that you are ready to approach your role professionally.\n\nREQUIRED CONFIRMATION:\n- I understand that my actions affect customers, teammates and the Milk Pop brand.\n- I understand that Milk Pop will provide training, tools and support, and that I am expected to work towards the standard.\n- I understand that communication, respect and dedication are central to the Milk Pop culture.\n- I understand that my final assessment has one attempt only and will be saved in my staff file."},
  {title: "Final Assessment Briefing", content: "You are about to begin the Module 1 Final Assessment.\n\nThis assessment is designed to test understanding, judgement and professional decision-making. It is not only a memory test.\n\nYou have one attempt only.\n\nOnce your answers are submitted, they cannot be changed. Your score, answers, completion date and result will be saved in your staff file.\n\nPassing score: 85%.\n\nStart only when you are ready."}
];
